      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Why G-Words Matter in Scrabble</h2>
      <p>G's true value isn't its 2-point face value — it's the sheer number of words it enables. The -ING ending appears in thousands of valid Scrabble words, and holding a G with I and N on your rack opens up massive bingo potential (all 7 tiles played for a 50-point bonus). Tournament players specifically track whether they have the "ING combo" as a rack-management strategy.</p>
      <p>Beyond suffixes, G combines powerfully with Z to form words like GRIZZLY (28 pts), GUZZLE (25 pts), and GLAZE (15 pts). The GZ combination creates some of the highest-scoring words in the entire Scrabble dictionary. Learning these combinations gives you weapons most casual players don't know exist.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Strategy for Playing G-Words</h2>
      <p>G plays differently depending on what stage of the game you're in. Here are the key approaches:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Hold G for -ING bingos:</strong> If you have G + I + N plus four other decent tiles, strongly consider playing for the bingo. The 50-point bonus for using all 7 tiles transforms your score. Common ING-bingos: PLAYING, GROWING, STAGING.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Pair G with Z aggressively:</strong> GAZE (14 pts), GLAZE (15 pts), GRAZE (15 pts) — these G+Z words are common enough to draw naturally and score well without premium squares.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Use G as a hook letter:</strong> G is an excellent back-hook — add it to create RUN → RUNG, SIN → SING, BAN → BANG. These hook plays create two words at once.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Don't hoard G too long:</strong> Unlike X or Z, G is only worth 2 points. If you don't have the ING combo forming within a turn or two, play your G for whatever it's worth rather than clogging your rack.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>GY- words for Y disposal:</strong> GYM (9 pts), GYRE (8 pts), GYPSY (14 pts) — if you're stuck with Y and G together, these words help you dispose of both efficiently.</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">The -ING Power Move</h2>
      <p>The -ING suffix is arguably the most important three-letter combination in Scrabble. With G on your rack plus I and N, you effectively have a "bingo engine" — the remaining four tiles just need to form a recognisable root word. Tournament players will sometimes sacrifice a few points on one turn to keep their ING combination intact for a potential 70+ point bingo on the next turn.</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Common bingo roots + ING:</strong> PLAY+ING, TALK+ING, DRAW+ING, WORK+ING, WALK+ING — everyday words that score 60-80+ points with the bingo bonus</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Less obvious bingos:</strong> QUAKING, BLAZING, FREEZING — these combine ING with high-value tiles for 80-100+ point plays</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Two-Letter G-Words for Tight Spots</h2>
      <p>When the board is cramped and long words won't fit, these two-letter G-words save you:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
